This example demonstrates Segment Routing over the MPLS data plane (SR-MPLS,
RFC 8660): signaling-free label programming, where every router derives its
own node-SID label-switching entries from a network-wide, statically
configured SID table (the model's stand-in for the OSPF-SR/IS-IS-SR
advertisements a real deployment would flood -- see the users guide's MPLS
chapter for the full simplification list), and an ingress ~SrPolicy module
imposes segment-list label stacks to steer specific flows.

Topology
--------

Six ~SrMplsRouter nodes (R1..R6) form a ring (R1-R2-R3-R4-R5-R6-R1), plus one
chord (R1-R3) that shortcuts across the ring, plus a second, higher-metric
parallel link between R1 and R2 (used for the adjacency-SID demo below).
hostA hangs off R1; three destination hosts (hostPlain, hostExplicit,
hostAdj) hang off R4 -- three "customers" reachable through the same egress
router, each reached by traffic engineered a different way.

All ring edges and the chord carry metric 1; the extra R1-R2 link carries
metric 10 (deliberately non-IGP-preferred). Router IDs are 1.1.1.1..6.6.6.6;
node SIDs are 1..6 (R1=1, ..., R6=6); with the default srgbBase (16000), R4's
node-SID label is 16004.

Only R1 carries an ~SrPolicy policy table (policies.xml), with three entries,
one per destination host -- each illustrating a different SR-MPLS traffic
steering mechanism:

1. hostA -> hostPlain, ``segments="node:4"`` (plain node-SID policy)

   Names only the destination's node SID; the path taken is whatever
   ~SegmentRouting's own shortest-path computation over the network picks.
   Here, that is the R1-R3 chord: a 2-hop shortcut (cost 2) that beats
   either way around the ring (cost 3). R1 (ingress) PUSHes label 16004 and
   forwards directly to R3 over the chord; R3, being R4's direct neighbor,
   POPs the label (penultimate-hop-popping, RFC 8660 Section 2) and
   forwards the resulting plain IP datagram to R4, which delivers it to
   hostPlain via ordinary L3 routing. No transit SWAP occurs on this path
   (R1-R3-R4 is only 2 hops).

2. hostA -> hostExplicit, ``segments="node:6 node:4"`` (explicit-path policy)

   Names R6's node SID as an intermediate waypoint before the real
   destination's node SID -- SR traffic engineering without any signaling
   protocol: a small number of loose waypoints steers an arbitrarily long
   detour, unlike RSVP-TE's explicit-route object, which must name every
   hop. Since R6 is R1's own direct neighbor (the ring edge), the R6 segment
   is dropped from the pushed stack entirely (pushing it would be pointless:
   R6's own PHP would immediately pop it back off -- see ~SrPolicy's
   first-segment canonicalization); only R4's label (16004) is actually
   pushed, and R1 forwards directly to R6. From R6, R4 is not a direct
   neighbor (R6 only reaches R4 via R5), so R6 genuinely transits: SWAP
   16004, forwarding to R5. R5, being R4's direct neighbor, POPs. The
   resulting 3-hop path (R1-R6-R5-R4) is deliberately longer than the
   chord's 2-hop shortcut -- proof that the policy, not the IGP metric,
   chose the route.

3. hostA -> hostAdj, ``segments="adj:ppp4 node:4"`` (adjacency-SID pin)

   Names one of R1's OWN local links by interface (R1's ppp4, the
   higher-metric SECONDARY link to R2) before R4's node SID. Adjacency-SID
   segments are always dropped when first (crossing the named link IS what
   forwarding out that interface already achieves -- see ~SrPolicy's
   Limitations section for why "adj:" segments only have well-defined
   semantics as a policy's first/sole segment in this model), so again only
   R4's label (16004) is pushed -- but this time R1 forwards out ppp4
   specifically, the SECONDARY link, even though the PRIMARY link to R2 is
   cheaper and would normally be preferred. From R2, R4 is not a direct
   neighbor (R2 only reaches R4 via R3), so R2 genuinely transits: SWAP
   16004, forwarding to R3, which POPs (R3 is R4's direct neighbor):
   crossing the pinned adjacency does not disturb the subsequent node-SID
   forwarding into R4.

   Note this policy names R1's interface directly ("adj:ppp4"), NOT R2's
   node SID as a waypoint -- unlike the explicit-path policy above, which
   deliberately avoids naming R2 at all as a waypoint. This is not a stylistic
   choice: R1 and R2 are joined by TWO parallel physical links (the primary,
   metric-1 one and this secondary, metric-10 one), and this model's ~Ted/
   ~LinkStateRouting represents a router PAIR's link state as a single entry
   keyed by the two routers' identities, not per physical interface. Once
   both links are flooded, only one of the two survives in the link-state
   view every OTHER router computes shortest paths from -- harmless for a
   pair with no competing alternate route, but here R1-R3-R2 (via the chord)
   IS a competing alternate, so a "node:2" waypoint would resolve
   unpredictably. The "adj:" mechanism sidesteps this entirely: it resolves
   straight to the named LOCAL interface at config time and never consults
   the link-state view, which is exactly why it is the correct tool for
   pinning one specific physical link among several parallel ones.

All three flows are simple periodic UDP flows (128-byte datagrams every
10 ms), started 0.1s apart so their PUSH/SWAP/POP log lines do not interleave
too closely; sim-time-limit is 10s, far longer than needed for delivery to
begin, leaving plenty of margin to inspect steady-state forwarding in Qtenv
or the Cmdenv EV log.

How to observe it
------------------

Run with Cmdenv and an "info" log level (the default in this ini) and grep
the output for ``doStackOps:`` lines, or look at which module logs
"Received ... from L2, label=16004" to see exactly which routers each flow's
labeled packets pass through. Compare:

- the plain flow's packets: PUSH at R1, POP at R3 -- R2, R5, and R6 never
  see this flow at all;
- the explicit-path flow's packets: PUSH at R1, SWAP at R6, POP at R5 --
  R2 and R3 never see this flow at all;
- the adjacency-pin flow's packets: PUSH at R1 (forwarded out ppp4, the
  secondary interface), SWAP at R2 (arriving over its SECONDARY-facing
  interface, not its primary one), POP at R3.

All three flows push the SAME label (16004, R4's node-SID label) and are
delivered to three different hosts behind the same router R4, yet each
takes a genuinely different physical path away from R1 -- that divergence,
not the label value, is what to look for.

Simplifications
---------------

As documented in the users guide's SR-MPLS section: the SID table is
static, network-wide configuration (no OSPF-SR/IS-IS-SR flooding is
modeled); the SRGB is homogeneous across all routers; there is no
protection/fast-reroute (a link or node failure reroutes node-SID traffic
via ~Ted's own shortest-path recomputation, once ~Ted itself notices the
failure -- see ~Ted's ``trackInterfaceState`` parameter -- but adjacency-SID
pins are NOT automatically protected, since they are tied to one specific
physical link by design).
